师，因为在交易完成之前他们不会得到报酬。而且我们在道德上并不灵活。所以那确实是一个艰难的时期。我记得我接受过采访，一些国家电视节目采访我并说，有什么，我们不知道什么？我说，大多数通过抵押贷款经纪人进行的评估都不值得他们写在纸上，我想说其中 75%。</p><p>里索兹：哇。</p><p>米勒：然后我受到了我所在行业的攻击，至少是当地竞争对手的攻击，他们在道德上非常灵活，而且做得很好。 2008 年，那位记者来找我说，这个人三年前就告诉我们这将会发生。</p><p>里索兹：（笑声）</p><p>米勒：从那时起，我显然变得更聪明了。</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>米勒：我也说过同样的话，但我是对的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：有时人们需要一段时间才能意识到他们听到的痛苦的事情，你知道，当有很多阻力时，这是因为你告诉人们他们不想听到的事情。</p><p>米勒：不想听，他们以旧的方式投资，事实上，当我开始对市场持负面态度时，我记得在《纽约时报》头版报道中价格下跌了 X% ，我记得一位不愿透露姓名的房地产经纪公司首席执行官打电话给我说：“你在做什么？”你知道，而且，你知道，“这是错误的。你不能说话。”我说——</p><p> RITHOLTZ：告诉他们真相。</p><p>米勒：你必须保持透明。对于该行业的信誉而言，真正有趣的是，有很多像我们发布的市场研究报告，但与 80 年代和 90 年代相比，经纪界对于正在发生的事情要透明得多，尽管并不完美，与雷曼兄弟倒闭的黑暗日子相反，我参加的小组中的经纪人说，这只会持续几周，一切都很好。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这始终是买卖的好时机。您还记得全国房地产协会的广告吗？</p><p>米勒：是的，我想你写了一篇关于-</p><p>里索兹：我可能有。</p><p>米勒：是的，过去 20 年里大约有一个月不是购买的好时机。</p><p>里索兹：太棒了。听着，如果您是佣金房地产经纪人，现在总是赚取佣金的好时机。</p><p>米勒：当然。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我妈妈是一名房地产经纪人，所以这总是餐桌上的谈话。和你一样，她也不害怕叫人出来。有趣的是，我们稍后会更多地讨论评估行业，但当时评估师并没有真正帮助买家。他们只是帮助经纪人通过这个过程获得银行贷款。</p><p>米勒：嗯，是的，有点像。我的意思是，基本上业内没有人理解并且在今天的房地产行业仍然不理解的是，当评估师为获得抵押贷款的买家进行评估时，他们的客户实际上是银行。</p><p>里索兹：对，没错。</p><p>米勒：现在，多德弗兰克法案出台后，该流程受到了各种限制，人们无法像他们一样与你交谈。</p><p>里索兹：回到过去。嘿，我有，我们正在支付这笔费用，这是我的抵押贷款金额。</p><p>米勒：这就是我需要的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：是的，保持公平。就像罗德尼和凯迪沙克一样。只要保持公平即可。</p><p>米勒：当时的说法是，这是一位优秀的评估师，擅长空中报价，并且善于翻译成数字。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以我总是对引用“可比较”的想法感到震惊。如果你正处于价格螺旋上升的阶段，而本质上是抵押贷款驱动的泡沫，那么可比产品有什么用呢？嘿，这条街上的房子贵了 30%。为这些人提供房屋抵押贷款，他们多付了 30%。没有多大意义。</p><p>米勒：是的，挑战在于，当我们评估房产估值时，我们关注的不仅仅是价格。价格有点像火车末端的守车。主要指标将是合同活动和挂牌库存，基于交易而不是基于价格。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：我想这会告诉银行，“嘿，如果这个买家将来拖欠抵押贷款，那么情况就是这样的。</p><p>米勒：我们认为抵押品不够。或者可以、会或不会。一个完美的例子就是，当你像傻瓜理论一样应用到 80 年代南佛罗里达州的房地产时，那里的木匠和护士都在翻转，辞掉工作，翻转房地产，赚了很多钱钱，然后他们就会转身以双倍、双倍、双倍的价格卖给别人。</p><p>如果你真的退一步看一下正在发生的事情的图表，你会发现价格直线上升，销量直线下降。你可以看到这一点，因为在许多情况下，销售实际上领先价格方向一年。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：事实上，在05年和06年，人们对金融危机的历史并不熟悉。价格达到顶峰，我想说——</p><p>米勒：06 年夏天。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：06 年，销量在 05 年达到顶峰。</p><p>米勒：正确。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：市场并没有开始下跌。市场在 07 年 10 月达到顶峰。</p><p>米勒：正确。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：所以你仍然拥有一个完整的股票市场。因此，在房地产市场见顶之后，你有一两年的时间才开始闪耀。确实，重的事情直到08年才开始。</p><p>米勒：这个问题的答案始终是，消费者，当他们不确定时，他们会停下来。所以你会看到交易量下降，但定价，这是更大的傻瓜理论，对吗？</p><p>里索兹：对。</p><p>米勒：继续下去，直到没有更多的买家，然后价格就是正确的。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：现在让我们翻转这个问题，谈谈卖家，因为目前我们所处的市场对于买家和卖家来说都有点具有挑战性，库存不足，抵押贷款利率要高得多。</p><p>卖家的运营似乎总是滞后 6 到 12 个月，甚至可能更长。</p><p>米勒：一到两年。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：一到两年，所以它们总是比价格落后一两年，当事情开始放缓并且价格开始滚动时-</p><p>米勒：他们调整得不快。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：他们真的不知道，当我看到一些价格时，我真的很震惊，“嘿，这是 2021 年 12 月的正确价格。”</p><p>米勒：对。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：但是那艘船已经起航了。”</p><p>米勒：嗯，你这么说很有趣，因为今年年初，当人们说，“你认为 2023 年会是什么样子？”我将 2023 年称为失望之年。因为人们不会得到 2021 年的价格，卖家也不会，但买家也不会看到价格大幅节省，价格也不会调整。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：库存太少了。</p><p>米勒：当你考虑房屋估值或市场趋势时，通常是在出现利率飙升等负面外部事件时，我们现在的库存崩溃了。因此，如果你看看利率，就会发现 30 年期固定利率是一年多前的两倍多。你预计销售会放缓，他们确实如此，你预计库存会堆积如山，但这并没有发生。事实上，目前新库存正在下降。新库存，意味着现在的库存实际上是负数，而且应该是-</p><p> RITHOLTZ：逐年比较。</p><p>米勒：是的，它应该是负数，它应该是上升的，但事实并非如此。所以，你不会看到价格下跌，因为我们实际上在第二季度就看到了，只要看看纽约市周围的郊区，比如韦斯特切斯特、拿骚县、费尔菲尔德县，房地产的市场份额在最近完成的季度成交中，根据地点的不同，所有成交销售的市场份额通常约为 45% 的交易进入竞价战，这意味着它们的成交价格高于交易的最后要价。当抵押贷款利率加倍时，这种情况就不会发生，对吗？这会让你的大脑崩溃，因为它是如此相反，这是因为库存因素是导致所有建模失败的原因。</p><p> RITHOLTZ：这些交易中有多少是与抵押贷款利率无关的现金交易？</p><p>米勒：对，所以在曼哈顿，第二季度现金交易的市场份额是历史上最高的，占交易的三分之二，大约是 65%。</p><p>里索兹：太棒了。</p><p> MILLER: Now, what&#39;s interesting if you dig a little deeper is that it&#39;s not that the whole world is just paying cash, it&#39;s that the number of transactions for cash buyers and financed buyers, both fell sharply year over year. The aggregate total was about 40% year over year.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Wow.</p><p> MILLER: But, and I&#39;m sort of making this simplistic, but cash buyers fell 20% and financed buyers fell 50%.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right.</p><p> MILLER: And so what it meant was there&#39;s a lot less resistance to your point of cash buyers. The other thing it says is that cash buyers skew higher in the sort of price strata. So one of the stories before the pandemic was Manhattan had almost eight and a half years of unsold supply. And that&#39;s including active inventory for new development, unsold condominiums, whether actively listed for sale or in shadow inventory that the developer could sort of dip into when they ran low of sales.</p><p> After the pandemic, and because of this, sort of the pandemic sort of introduced strength to the high-end market, the share of, or the activity continued to favor the high end of the market. So instead of being a market that was sort of the low end was where all the action was, it became a market where the high end was strong because the share of unsold condos fell from 8.3 years to about just over three years, meaning it fell by more than half in terms of what it would take to sell off the supply in New York. It was dramatic.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So there&#39;s normally a chain of sales. The starter home, the move up, right? There&#39;s a whole run of this. But during the pandemic, a lot of people just said, I&#39;m going to go buy a second home or a third home, a vacation property, so I&#39;m not stuck in a city where I can&#39;t do anything in a tiny apartment, and that really sucked up a lot of supply.</p><p> MILLER: Yeah, the way I look at it is in the city itself, in Manhattan and most urban centers, sales activity fell by half, and it fell by half because during a global pandemic in a multifamily building, are you going to let strangers into your apartment, right?</p><p> The thinking was, no.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: (LAUGHTER)</p><p> MILLER: But in reality, the buyers that zoomed out to the suburbs were largely from the rental market because they weren&#39;t anchored to another asset.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: They didn&#39;t have to sell.</p><p> MILLER: The affluent, yeah, they bought in the Hamptons, a second primary home, I called it co-primary at the time. And high-end markets in the county surrounding New York definitely did better, and people moved farther. I mean, my wife and I moved a half an hour farther from the city because we figured we weren&#39;t going to be going into the city five days a week.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right. And you get a lot more bang for your buck the further away you are.</p><p> MILLER: Correct.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So more property, you live on a compound with how many different buildings on that property in Connecticut?</p><p> MILLER: Three.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: That&#39;s a lot of buildings. So you couldn&#39;t get that in Darien, right?</p><p> You couldn&#39;t get that near the water or near a commuter line into the city, at least not for a reasonable price. So we&#39;ll come back to a lot of what&#39;s going on in New York and the rest of the real estate market. I just want to touch on one more aspect of your background. You&#39;re a professor at Columbia Business School teaching a course on commercial real estate. Tell us a little bit about that experience. What&#39;s the course like and what are the students like at Columbia Business School?</p><p> MILLER: Well, it&#39;s their architecture school. It&#39;s the master&#39;s in real estate development.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: So not business school, architecture school.</p><p> MILLER: Architecture school. It&#39;s a master&#39;s in real estate development. And so my students are mostly in their 23 to 29, super smart and very eager to get into the business. And so what it has allowed me as a venue, I teach every summer, it&#39;s not year round. I usually have about 150 students. When we were Zooming during the pandemic, I had like 190, which there&#39;s a lot of icons in your Zoom screen, right?</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, you&#39;ve got five or six panels in.</p><p> MILLER: But the program is fantastic, and I&#39;m one of those people that run up and down the aisles, asking questions.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: High-fiving the students.</p><p> MILLER: Yeah, talking, and the other sort of secret passion is I get to tell the same dad jokes every year because they haven&#39;t heard &#39;em before, or they have, but not from me.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: It&#39;s a whole new crop of new audience.</p><p> MILLER: Victims, well, students, right.</p><p> RITHOLTZ: Right, that&#39;s hilarious.</p><p> MILLER: And there&#39;s nothin